3. Anonymous Blocks vs Named Blocks
Anonymous Block

An anonymous block is a PL/SQL block without a name.

Characteristics
Executed only once.
Not stored in the database.
Cannot be reused directly.
Example
BEGIN
   DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Hello World');
END;
/
Use Cases
Testing code
Simple calculations
Temporary tasks
Named Block

A named block has a name and is stored in the database.

Examples:

Procedures
Functions
Packages
Triggers
Example (Procedure)
CREATE OR REPLACE PROCEDURE greet
AS
BEGIN
   DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Hello World');
END;
/

Execute:

EXEC greet;
Characteristics
Stored in database.
Can be reused.
Easier maintenance.
Better for large applications.
